04312nam a22005775i 9780804779111DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202011cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047791117 a10.1515/97808047791112doi  a(DE-B1597)564678  a(OCoLC)1198931934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aB105.I47bR45 2011eb 7aPHI0180002bisacsh04a121/.6822200aReleasing the Image :bFrom Literature to New Media /cJacques Khalip, Robert Mitchell, Mark Hansen, Cesare Casarino, Peter Geimer, Giorgio Agamben. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIntroduction. Release-(non-)origination-concepts -- tOne. "Self-generated" images -- tTwo. Cézanne's certitude -- tThree. Nymphs -- tFour. From fixed to fluid: material-mental images between neural synchronization and computational mediation -- tFive. When the ear dreams: dolby digital and the imagination of sound -- tSix. Imaging sound in new media art: asia acoustics, distributed -- tSeven. Three theses on the life-image (deleuze, cinema, bio-politics) -- tEight. On producing the concept of the image-concept -- tNine. The romantic image of the intentional structure -- tTen. Ur-ability: force and image from kant to benjamin -- tEleven. The tongue of the eye: what "art history" means -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt has become a commonplace that "images" were central to the twentieth century and that their role will be even more powerful in the twenty-first. But what is an image and what can an image be? Releasing the Image understands images as something beyond mere representations of things. Releasing images from that function, it shows them to be self-referential and self-generative, and in this way capable of producing forms of engagement beyond spectatorship and subjectivity. This understanding of images owes much to phenomenology-the work of Husserl, Heidegger, and Merleau-Ponty-and to Gilles Deleuze's post-phenomenological work. The essays included here cover historical periods from the Romantic era to the present and address a range of topics, from Cézanne's painting, to images in poetry, to contemporary audiovisual art. They reveal the aesthetic, ethical, and political stakes of the project of releasing images and provoke new ways of engaging with embodiment, agency, history, and technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aImage (Philosophy). 0aPhenomenology. 0aPhilosophy, Modern. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aAgamben, Giorgio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCasarino, Cesare, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeimer, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHansen, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKhalip, Jacques, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMitchell, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477911140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804779111423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804779111.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles